an “appropriate” fertility level.

102
00:08:23,280 --> 00:08:28,400
Li didn’t say exactly what appropriate\h
fertility levels were, but here's a hint.

103
00:08:29,200 --> 00:08:33,440
State propaganda slogans are telling\h
couples to “have children for the country.”

104
00:08:34,560 --> 00:08:39,840
Yes, lie back and think of China.\h
That’s probably not going to work.

105
00:08:40,880 --> 00:08:42,880
There are other ideas that might work better.\h\h

106
00:08:43,520 --> 00:08:47,360
“Measures now being discussed range\h
from extending maternity leave\h\h

107
00:08:47,360 --> 00:08:52,560
to encouraging people to have a second child\h
with straight cash incentives or tax breaks.”

108
00:08:53,360 --> 00:08:58,080
But possibly not. Similar\h
policies have been tried in Japan,\h\h

109
00:08:58,080 --> 00:09:01,840
Taiwan, and South Korea\h
after their birthrates fell.\h\h

110
00:09:01,840 --> 00:09:07,760
Things like baby bonuses, new parental leave\h
policies, and expanded preschool availability.

111
00:09:07,760 --> 00:09:08,560
And they didn’t work.

112
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:13,920
But if incentives don’t work, the\h
Chinese Communist Party can use\h\h

113
00:09:13,920 --> 00:09:19,440
propaganda and social pressure. One example\h
of this is the “leftover women” campaign.

114
00:09:20,080 --> 00:09:26,080
That’s a propaganda campaign aimed at shaming\h
educated women into getting married earlier,\h\h

115
00:09:26,080 --> 00:09:31,280
by trying to convince them that if they’re\h
over 27 and unmarried, no one will want them.

116
00:09:32,640 --> 00:09:37,040
And it’s worked, in the sense that it’s\h
given Chinese women in their mid-20s\h\h

117
00:09:37,040 --> 00:09:39,040
